segments.text: Testing.
One, two, three.
I guess you might as well just start out and you might as well just talk about death for a minute.
I had the essay from the first time you ever saw a dead man.
And I realized that you were a child.
And death is a part of life out here, too.
Very much.
And let me tell you that I wasn't but 18 years old when I was called on to come and help dress a corpse.
To dress a, yeah.
And you know, that's something that people don't touch their bodies anymore.
They send them on.
But I was 18 years old.
And Miss came back, called me, and she said, you're just as well to learn.
You have to face it sooner or later.
And I said, oh, I just don't believe it.
She said, oh, yes, you can.
And she sighed, and she put her hands on my shoulders.
And she looked me straight in the eye.
She says, honey, dead people don't hurt you.
It's the live ones that give you trouble.
So these have laid all of their troubles down, and the least we can do is to make it pleasant for them for their last minutes here on this earth.
And she says, Do you know when you go take a bath how much better that you feel and how much you really enjoy it?
I said, Yes.
She said,
Well, when we wash all of this earthly feeding off of this body and put it in God's hands, we've done one of the greatest things that you can do for humanity.
and I thought, I've never heard anyone express it like that.
She said, that's the last respects that you can pay that person and put them in God's care.
So you washed the body.
So I washed the body, and I will never forget it if I live to be a million years old.
That was a big chore.
But then when she said, and you turn it over to God, and it's in his care.
It's clean.
She says, when the baby comes, you wash it with earthly water.
Wash it in earthly water and return it to God who gave it.
No one had ever talked to me like that.
No one had ever said anything to me like that.
So I have, I think, I thought that that was one of the sweetest ways to learn that ever was.
It is.
It was hard.
I bet it was.
And I do understand.
I mean, I know, too, that there's a kindness in a death.
Sure.
That doesn't show up at any other time in this country.
No.
But the day we're born, there's a time set aside for our deaths.
And regardless of what comes, it's going to be there.
It's going to be there.
And...
God has a purpose for all of us.
And we have a job to do.
It may take us a long time to find it and to fly right to get it.
But we have it, and we'll do it.
And you said you believe that your purpose in life, that you still have purpose.
I remember, I'm going to go back to the time that I met you,
Because that's of a very important value to me.
And that is the time that you had that massive heart attack and you were giving up.
And I remember, I remember that you just made a decision.
I hope I played a role in it.
I like to think that I did.
You sure did.
And you, of course, have fulfilled the purpose of my life since.
And I'm glad that you decided not
To give up working on life and helping other people, because that's what you've done.
You know, I really thought that my day's work was over.
I did, too.
I didn't know.
I was scared.
I really did.
I really thought, well, this is the end.
I can't make a comeback now.
I'm too old.
Yeah.
Well, I think you can...
My grandfather always said, hold to the end of the road.
Hold to the end of the road.
Never leave it shabby.
All right.
I didn't hold to the end of the road.
There was something left for me to do.
Now, what it is right now,
I actually believe this with all my heart.
And I believe it stronger today than I've ever believed it before, is helping little folks like I help today.
Having those three little children to come, and actually the first time in their life to know what they were doing.
To me, that is worth...
A lifetime.
Now, to get out here and for praise for the public, I wouldn't give you two cents and a half.
But God knows what I was doing.
And he knew I was working to make better children.
And he knows what I do.
Now, Ava, I know, I just, I think above race, creed, or color, it doesn't matter to you.
I don't.
It don't matter one bit.
You have such a value to go on and to do that kind of work in this world.
I've watched you do it.
And it stems from that belief that you do row to the end of the, you know, the hole to the end of the rope.
The end of the rope.
And you do what has to be done.
That's true.
There was a little German.
There was a little, well.
Yeah, from Guatemala, you said?
Guatemala.
Uh-huh.
And then this other little boy was born in the Yucatan.
Yeah.
He was from Guatemala, too.
Yeah, somewhere down there.
Yeah.
All right.
Now they're all different.
And they've come up under different environments.
And all together different ways of life.
You didn't see any difference shown in those children.
No, they were all children.
They were all children to me.
They were all God's children.
And I was put here to help them.
Well, like I see on that wall, I see the certificate of a tree that's been planted.
And I'm going to get that down and read it right now because I know what it says, okay?
I just love it.
Because it's the victory forest in Jerusalem, right?
That's right.
And that's in honor of a great teacher, Ms. Ava Johnson Cox, from a thankful student.
That's Eileen Balinski.
That's pretty terrific.
Not many.
How many people do you know that have a tree planted?
Well, I don't.
You don't know too many.
No, uh-uh.
You don't, and that's really nice.
Nice?
Yeah, it's beautiful.
To me, it's one of the greatest things that ever happened.
Yeah, everything.
I don't want people, when I die, to get up and say, oh, she was a wonderful person, she did this, she did that.
All I want that minister to say, this woman lived.
And when I say lived, she lived every day to the fullest extent.
She gave her all, regardless of whatever it was she had to do.
And I do.
I put out every ounce of energy that's in my body for whatever I've got to do that day.
And hope
that I have another day coming to do.
This one is the Texas Department of Aid on Aging Certificate of Appreciation to Ava Johnson Cox for volunteer service to older Texans.
And that's signed by the governor.
And a Republican at that.
Yeah, I noticed that.
I will have to say Clements signed it.
We'll excuse that.
But that's a grant.
And that's Augusta Lucia?
How do you say that?
Augusta Lucia, Jr. And who is?
She's the Hebrew girl.
Is she?
Yeah.
Uh-huh.
The chairman or president of the Texas Department on Aging?
And you feel proud of things like that, Saban.
Well, that's what I say.
You said I had no feeling of class, color, or creed, and I don't.
I know.
You don't.
You really don't.
Well, I go back and, you know, I do.
Just look at Armando yesterday.
I know.
Just as thrilled to see him come out, put his arms around me and kiss me.
I know.
Just as good a Mexican as ever lived.
That's right.
A question, too, I want to ask you here, because, again, every now and then, you know, we have to refer to

the to Lyndon because he affected your life because of who he was and again I want to ask you if you think people say about him that he didn't really believe in those civil rights policies that they belong to JFK
You know what I'm talking about.
Yes, I know.
But that he didn't really have that incentive.
But I want to know, do you think he did or do you think he didn't?
He doggone sure did.
Because it comes from you, from your family.
Yes, it comes from our family tree.
And I'll tell you, he loved those people.
Now, he really did.
He pushed civil rights from JFK.
Yes, sir.
He pushed it not from JFK.
He pushed it because he believed in it.
Okay, that I want to say to you.
And he told me when I went to San Antonio to teach, that's the greatest thing that I ever did in my life.
And that I...
God would reward me for what I had done for those little Mexican children.
Because you taught in a minority program.
I certainly did.
You went straight to do that.
That's all I did.
Right.
Now, what school was that that you taught in?
Well, I first started out in John F. Kennedy in San Antonio.
Okay.
And, well, it was all in Edgewood District.
Edgewood, right.
And that's the poorest district there in San Antonio.
Right.
And Stani, Stano, uh...

steinheiser was my principal and he was the best thing to me that ever was and he knew that i had that little mexican feelings at heart and he he did everything he could to help me he was a good man yeah and i'm not sorry for for working as hard as i did i'd do it again tomorrow you drove
Before you moved to San Antonio, I know how you got your education.
Did you just stop planting tomatoes one day and made a decision you were going to do something?
I said that was the hardest work I ever did in my life, and I could make a living a lot easier than I could working two acres of tomatoes with a hoe.
So I bundled up my little self and went to San Marcos in the summer of 48.
And I started out with 12 hours that I had gotten back in 19 and 23 and 24.
And that was two hour courses at a time.
That's all the college credits that I had.
Got a certificate standing for it that summer.
That type, yeah.
You know, that type.
Well, I got a four-year certificate because I made an average of 85 on all my courses.
Well, anyway, a six-year certificate.
That's what it was.
If you make an average of 85, you get a six-year.
And if you make an average of 75, you get a four-year.
Minus 85, thank goodness.
I did have a little sense then.
So anyway.
I got my certificate.
I enrolled in the fall semester.
I taught school every day and went to school every night.
And in 1950, I walked down the aisle with my BS degree.
And I taught school every day.
And 1952, I got my master's degree.
But I took it easy.
I just didn't go every night to school.
You went?
On Saturdays.
You went to school on Saturdays.
Every Saturday.
In order to get your master's degree.
To get my master's degree.
And you did that at Trinity, though, didn't you?
At San Antonio.
I got my BS degree at Trinity and my master's degree at St. Mark's.
But I want to tell you right now, I took work at the University of Texas.
I took work at Lubbock.
I took work at Arkansas and Sam Houston, A&M.
I believe that's all.
And the hardest school of all of them is Trinity University.
Don't kid yourself.
You've really got to get out and get with it.
Oh, I did too.
I took some Bible study out at the Lady of the Lake.
I'll tell you that.
I took history of the Bible, and that made me sit up and take notice.
Then I took the Old Testament.
Then I took the New Testament.
I've had it.
And it was hard.
But in order to understand our history, if you don't understand the Jewish or Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob's laws and the beginning of this thing, it's just hard for you to ever get it down.
Well, that's something I want to ask you about religion.
I'm aware that in Texas...
We have a new religion, and it's the New Testament.
But the old-time religions in Texas didn't just start there.
They began in the beginning.
God created the earth and taught through Genesis on up.
And I wonder if today's religion isn't short-sighting itself, because this community is still an old community.
And I know it's an Old Testament community.
Well, it's just, I think that's the reason most of these broke off from the Methodist Church.
It's still the old Methodist Church.
I can remember, as a little girl, we came in the Methodist Church, we knelt.
That was God's house.
And we came in.
We were quiet.
And we knelt.
We went to our pew.
We knelt.
We made the sign of the cross and we said our prayer while we were there.
It was quietly said, but we said it.
There was a cross up in the front.
We knew what that cross signified.
Today, you just walk in that church and they start talking and they visit and they yak, yak, yak.
That I just cannot take.
That is sacred.
And in the temple, don't you remember, they were cast out because they did that?
And I can't tell.
There's something in me that boils up that I can't help.
I know.
And I like to go to the Pentecostal church and hear them because they do have lots of good services.
But I can't stand the screaming because in the beginning, God said that couldn't be.
Yeah.
And in the temple, when they began to carry on like that, they were let out.
And I guess I'm just, I don't know what's wrong with me.
How do you feel that things have a sacredness?
There's a sacredness that I can't get away from.
And I know one thing.
I got up and walked out of church one time, and I don't think I was over it.

six or seven years old of course we didn't have such things the bathroom but i had to tinkle and i got up and walked out of the church and my daddy just blistered my little seat good because i didn't whisper to him and tell him that i needed to go to the bathroom i got up and walked out of the church and walked around behind the old hack and sat down and tinkled
all right he said little girls don't do things like that little girls don't nice little girls don't get up and leave while the minister's talking nice little girls
Don't interrupt services by walking out.
Well, I got knees.
Now, that's three things I want you to remember.
And I got three swats for each of them.
That was nine swats.
I remember them.
I remember.
Every time you were also disciplined as a child, you were disciplined with a principle.
Isn't that true?
That's right.
Every time there was a reason for it.
Yeah, that's important.
Oh, and I tell you right now, I'd rather to have been whipped so many times than for my daddy to sit down and talk to me.
Talking to you was worse than getting stanky.
He'd set me on his lap and he'd say, my little princess did me wrong.
I didn't think that she'd ever do that.
And she... Honey, why did you do that?
What made you?
Oh.
I hurt my daddy's feelings.
Oh, that was bad.
But again...
You know, I think of the things back to education and how many years you worked in San Antonio.
How many years again was it?
I have it on that other tape.
I went there in 63 and I left in 73.
73, working with minority children all this time or both?
Both.
I went then over to the Colonies North, the Butter District, but I still had the same problems.
Oh, I know.
But I don't, I feel so much enriched.
They gave me a sense of feeling that I had
opened the door for them and made them feel better.
Yeah.
And you know, that's just worth a lot to anybody.
Oh, it is.
It is.
Now, you learned to speak Spanish, too.
Yes, I learned to speak Spanish and I taught Spanish.
Yeah.
I taught...
You didn't feel like it was a burden to learn Spanish so you could teach it, did you?
You felt it was important?
I thought it was very important.
I think it is important today.
And let me tell you, we're the only nation in the world that doesn't have two languages taught.
The only one.
And I think it's wrong.
We need a second language.
We do.
And I'm proud that I can talk enough German to get by.
I'm happy.
You speak German, you speak Spanish, you speak English.
That's right.
I'm happy.
I have my pen in there from...
When you talk about ranching being a labor of love, you love your land, you love your stock, and you enjoy doing what you're doing.
And I don't care where you would, my father would take me, he would always say, look at the land.
and get your bearings, you came this way.
And if you're lost, see what kind of a tree this is.
Is it bent over?
Is it straight?
Is it a mesquite?
We didn't have any mesquites in this country back in 1900.
There wasn't any mesquites.
Right.
Well, all right.
We had one mesquite on 1,500 acres.
Today, we're poisoning mosquitoes on the same land.
I want to ask, right, yeah.
Why?
I know it's true.
The beans are very, very rich in protein.
And the cattle eat them.
The goats eat them.
The horses eat them.
Everything eats them.
But.
It doesn't destroy it.
And they come back up.
They pass through, they're germinated, and they come up.
And we never get rid of them.
Never.
I wanted to ask you, what about the grass fires?
You know, the ones that spread all across the state and burn for ever and ever?
For miles and miles.
We've had one couple in our county this year, which...
was a misfortune and it was merely an accident.
Really it was.
The wind, it was out and everything, or they thought it was out for a couple of days.
But I know that the average person that I would talk to don't know what spunk wood is.
But we have it in this country.
And spunk wood is.
And spunk wood kept burning just barely a little at a time, just enough to keep it warm.
Then the wind changed and blew this spunk wood, as we call it,

into grass then it got started and away it went and we certainly had a grass fire here that destroyed thousands and thousands of acres and fences but when I lived on the ranch and this is the first time and I've been living here since 1912
And this is the first time that I've ever seen a fire that lingered as long as this one here.
Yeah, I heard about it.
And it was bad.
But people, when you talk to them about spunk wood, they laugh at you.
But it's just old, rotten wood that really hasn't all decayed.
And...
But it has enough life in it that when it is fired, it stays alive.
It stays alive and alive and alive.
Almost like peach bogs.
Absolutely.
And it is the hardest stuff in the world to put out.
And that's exactly what happened.
Well, I know that the pioneers talk about seeing these fires come and that settlers here fought and fought and fought because these things just swept the Great Plains for years.
Sure they did.
I have my grandmother's diary here and up there on the old ranch.
It says that the grass was up to the horse's stomach.
That's very true.
We have grass in wet years on that place up there because it was a spring and it was sub-irrigated all the way down and all around that
40 acres that we sold to the park was all sub-irrigated from that spring.
And when we dug that spring out in 1926, we dug up many, many bones of cattle.
Oh, I mean of cows and horses and mules.
We knew what kind of bones they were because naturally we had seen them.
And lots of animals.
What I mean by that, fox and squirrel.
You can tell a red bone where it comes from, what type of animal it is in a red bone.
Now, you may not understand what I mean by red bone animals.
But they do have a red bone.
A squirrel is a red bone animal.
Oh, really?
That's right, if you don't believe me.
Well, that's true.
And that's the thing that I don't understand about people today.
But I guess it's because they have never been told.
No, they've never been told.
And they've never had to know these things.
But I was told when I was quite small about red bone animals.
In fact, they didn't insist that you eat them.
Oh, really?
That's right.
But during the Hoover days, I ate plenty of red bone animals.
A lot of squirrel?
A lot of squirrel.
You betcha.
I have too, I know.
And they'll tell you that jackrabbits are no good.
They'll tell you that cottontails are no good.
But if that were the truth, I'd be dead today.
That's all you had to eat.
My mother would say, no meat in the house.
If you want meat today, you've got to get it.
Right.
Well, I want to tell you one thing.
We didn't have money to buy bullets.
So how do you think we got them?
I don't know.
Tell me.
Well, you don't say it today because that's awful.
We killed him with a nigger shooter.
But they tell you a slingshot.
Well, a slingshot is two long strings of...
with a piece of leather in connecting it, and you sling it around like that and let her fly.
But a nigger shooter is made with a stock.
Now, it's called that because of what it was used for.
That's right, but if you say a nigger shooter today, they just give you them.
Well, I think that in American history, we need to know that it was used to...
keep people in the fields, right?
That's exactly what it was used for.
It was to, I'm looking at you, and you're picking cotton, and you're my slave, right?
That's right.
Now, that's something that people don't want to face.
They don't want to face it, but that is the bare fact.
That's what it is.
And so help me goodness, they don't know why it was called a nigger shooter.
But that's bare facts, and that is exactly right.
Well, it's our American historical shame coming out again, but it's the reality that that's what it was.
I like that little Dutch boy.
I ain't got much shame here.
That's truth, and they don't know it.
That's an artifact of American history.
And people need to know why.
Well, I was called up on the carpet because I picked it up off the bed, and I said, this is a nigger shooter, and Lennon was as good with a nigger shooter as the next one.
Lennon had an acrid eye, and don't let anybody kid you.
He was good with a nigger shooter.
He was good.
with a gun, and don't let them ever tell you that he couldn't shoot.
Because it became a device for hunting as a weapon.
I think that sounded right.
That's right.
We used it.
We didn't have money to buy bullets with, and we used this nigger shooter.
And we used a slingshot.
And a slingshot was what David killed Goliath with.
That's exactly right.
It's a sling, and it's a slide shot.
And we had to have a certain type of rock for that.
And there's plenty of rocks, but you'd fill your pockets full of them.
We'd kill them in your squirrel with a slingshot.
